<h2><b>Breeze::OS Installer -- Drive Partitioning Schemes</b></h2>
<p>
To the left are settings for <b>hard-drive</b> partitioning <b>schemes</b>.<br>
The schemes differ based on the disk types of <font color="#33FB01">normal</font> or <font color="#33FB01">lvm</font>.<br>Specify whether or not your drive is a <b>4K drive</b> using <font color="#33FB01">sector size</font>.<br>The scheme <font color="#33FB01">root</font> uses <b>most</b> of the drive for a <b>single</b> partition.<br>The offered schemes create the following partitions:
<ul>
<li>a <font color="#33FB01">/boot</font> partition, for boot loaders,
<li>a <font color="#33FB01">/</font> <b>root</b> partition where <b>/usr</b> is located,
<li>a <font color="#33FB01">/home</font> partition for user files,
<li>a <font color="#33FB01">/var</font> partition, for system and log files (+home),
<li>a <font color="#33FB01">/srv</font> partition for HTTP, NFS, FTP, etc. files (+home, +var),
<li>a <font color="#33FB01">/share</font> partition, as a <b>common</b> area (+home, +var, +srv), and
<li>a <font color="#33FB01">/opt</font> partition for third-party software (+home, +var, +srv, +share),
</ul>
<b>/share</b> should not be confused with <b>/usr/share</b>.<br>It is used to store common repositories (git), archives, etc.<br>
You can still choose to rename mount points, other<br>than <b>/ root</b>, <b>swap</b>, <b>boot</b>, and <b>home</b>, before formatting.<br>
If you are <b>upgrading</b>, and chose to keep your <b>/home</b> partition; then,<br>you <font color="red"><b>must</b></font> select the scheme which matches your drive partitioning.
</p>
<p>
Click on <a href="action=apply"><img width="16" height="16" src="install/images/apply.png"></a> to <b>Save your Settings</b>.<br>
Click on <a href="action=continue"><img width="16" height="16" src="install/images/next.png"></a> to <b>Continue</b>.
</p>
